\description{
Interpolates per-analyte grab chemistry onto a daily date grid and computes
msPAF for every day within the requested date range.  The result is a tidy
tibble with one row per (site \eqn{\times} day), suitable for trend
analysis, visualisation, and downstream \code{\link[=time_weighted_aggregate]{time_weighted_aggregate()}} calls.
}
\details{
\code{mspaf_daily()} returns one of \strong{two distinct products}, chosen by
\code{ndraws}; they answer different questions and should not be expected to
coincide:
\itemize{
\item \strong{Deterministic} (\code{ndraws = NULL}, default).  A single grabs-exact daily
line: the residual smoother is pinned to the measured grab samples, so the
curve threads the reported lab values.  \emph{Pro:} fast, reproducible, the best
single-number estimate; ideal as a sanity check.  \emph{Con:} carries no
uncertainty and over-fits noisy grabs.
\item \strong{Draws} (\code{ndraws > 0}).  A Monte-Carlo posterior propagating trend
(GAM) and between-grab (OU bridge) uncertainty, plus grab measurement error
when \code{grab_cv} is set.  \code{return = "summary"} reports the central tendency
plus a credible band; \code{return = "draws"} returns per-draw paths.  \emph{Pro:}
honest uncertainty quantification.  \emph{Con:} the central estimate is
seed/\code{ndraws}-dependent and, by Jensen's inequality on the bounded msPAF
index, generally differs from the deterministic line.
}

The summary centre is a summary \emph{of the draws} (issue #42), so it always lies
within its own credible band; it is not the deterministic line overlaid on a
band built from a different posterior.
}
\section{Interpolation}{

Each analyte is interpolated independently:
\itemize{
\item \code{"forward_fill"} carries the last directly observed value forward
until the next grab.  Produces a step function.
\item \code{"linear"} linearly interpolates between consecutive observations.
For SSD-eligible toxicants (metals, ammonia), interpolation is performed
in log-concentration space, which is more appropriate for log-normally
distributed data and avoids negative intermediate values.  Co-analytes
(pH, temperature, DOC, hardness) are interpolated linearly.
\item \code{"model"} fits a season-blind \code{\link[=fit_target_model]{fit_target_model()}} on the grab
chemistry and the supplied \code{reference_model}, and predicts each
toxicant's concentration between grabs as
\code{reference + impact}, where the impact (the leachate-attributable
increment) is modelled from hydrology and a persistent latent state but
\strong{never} from day-of-year. Co-analytes are forward-filled. Requires
\code{reference_model}; see \code{\link[=fit_target_model]{fit_target_model()}} for the method.
}
Below-detection values are treated as their detection-limit value for
interpolation purposes, matching the treatment in \code{\link[=add_mspaf]{add_mspaf()}}.
}

\section{Leading edge}{

Days before the first grab sample for an analyte are outside the observation
record:
\itemize{
\item \code{"drop"} (default) excludes such days from the output.
\item \code{"backfill"} assigns the first observed value to all earlier days.
Use cautiously -- it assumes the analyte was at its first observed level
before sampling commenced.
}
}

\section{Temperature for ammonia}{

When \code{NH3-N} is in \code{df}, water temperature is required per sample for the
un-ionised fraction normalisation.  Two sources are accepted:
\itemize{
\item Temperature rows already in \code{df} (measured on grab-sample days) are
interpolated along with other analytes.
\item An external daily temperature series supplied via the \code{temperature}
argument (e.g. from \code{\link[=estimate_water_temp]{estimate_water_temp()}}) fills in days without a
grab temperature.  Grab-sample-day measurements take priority.
}
Set \code{require_temperature = FALSE} only for datasets that do not contain
ammonia.
}

\section{Interpreting gap uncertainty}{

In draws mode the width of the band across an observation gap is the honest
posterior \strong{only under ignorable (MAR) missingness}.  Where you have
external grounds that a gap was quiescent (informative/MNAR sampling), the
ignorable band over-states uncertainty there.  The \code{"bracket"} output gives
both extremes: read the \strong{informative} (lower) envelope where you vouch the
gap was quiet, the \strong{ignorable} (upper) envelope otherwise.  The
\code{precautionary_lo}/\code{precautionary_hi} columns are the composite
\verb{[lo_informative, hi_ignorable]} — a \strong{decision bound, not a calibrated
credible interval} (its coverage exceeds nominal and is undefined).  Applied
blanket, the informative envelope under-covers genuinely eventful gaps, so use
it per-gap; automatic per-gap conditioning on a continuous proxy is future
work (#18).  The \code{deterministic} line is \strong{not} a safe blanket alternative —
it under-states risk by Jensen's inequality (#39/#42).
}

